In 2001, a secret memo concluded that President George W. Bush had the authority to wage preemptive war against terrorists and countries not linked to 9/11.
The memo allowed for military action against terrorist organizations or states supporting them, even without specific ties to 9/11.
Attorney General nominee Alberto Gonzales promised to abide by anti-torture treaties, despite past criticisms.
Gonzales sought legal rulings on extreme interrogation practices in the name of national security.
The debate over torture memos involving John Yoo continues, with questions about the extent of senior officials' knowledge.
The issue of prisoner abuse remains a stain on the administration.
